		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2024"></a><br><code>sle2024/paper06</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024</a> paper:</span><br><i>The Design of a Self-Compiling C Transpiler Targeting POSIX Shell</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/LaurentHuberdeau.html">Laurent Huberdeau</a>, <a href="../profile/CassandreHamel.html">Cassandre Hamel</a>, <a href="../profile/StefanMonnier.html">Stefan Monnier</a>, <a href="../profile/MarcFeeley.html">Marc Feeley</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3687997.3695639">10.1145/3687997.3695639</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagM">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> The work centers on a compilation/transpilation pipeline from (a subset of) C down to POSIX shell code.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2d.html"><span class="tagL">T2D: Deployment</span></a><ul><li> Targeting POSIX shell is motivated by portability and deployability on minimal Unix-like environments.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL">T3D: GPLs</span></a><ul><li> It directly concerns general-purpose languages (C and POSIX shell) rather than a narrowly scoped DSL.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> A key concern is the practicality/efficiency of generated shell code and the bootstrapped compiler.
</li></ul></li></ul>
